Everything is in place. Here's a summary of what was done:

## Changes Made

### 1. `handle_grep` — Surface `rejected_flags` to the user (line 1441-1447)

Added a check at the top of `handle_grep`, immediately after parsing succeeds. If `args.rejected_flags` is non-empty, each rejection message is printed as a red error and the function returns early — before any grep process is spawned.

### 2. 10 new tests added

• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_json_flag`** — verifies `--json` populates `rejected_flags`
• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_jsonl_flag`** — verifies `--jsonl` rejection
• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_null_flag`** — verifies `-Z` rejection
• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_long_null_flag`** — verifies `--null` rejection
• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_only_matching_flag`** — verifies `-o` rejection
• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_format_flag`** — verifies `--format json` rejection (and that format's value is consumed)
• **`parse_grep_args_rejects_max_count_flag`** — verifies `-m 5` rejection
• **`parse_grep_args_silently_ignores_color_flags`** — verifies `--color`/`--no-color` are silently ignored (empty `rejected_flags`)
• **`parse_grep_args_valid_flags_still_work`** — verifies `-s`, `-C`, `--include` still work and leave `rejected_flags` empty
• **`parse_grep_args_rejected_flags_dont_block_pattern`** — verifies that even with multiple rejected flags, pattern and path are still parsed correctly

